The concept map organizes Computer Vision into a clear pyramid hierarchy, moving upwards from raw pixel processing to cognitive reasoning.

Low-Level Processing forms the foundation, operating directly on input image pixels to execute noise filtering and color space transformations.

This bottom layer extracts primitive features like edges, shapes, and textures, leveraging classic literature examples such as Canny's edge detection and SIFT/SURF descriptors.

The output flows up into Mid-Level Analysis, which groups these low-level primitives into mathematically meaningful structures and regions.

This mid-tier handles tasks like image segmentation, object detection (bounding boxes), classification (labels), and motion tracking over time.

The mid-level analysis integrates seminal deep learning and localization breakthroughs, citing architectures like YOLO (Redmon et al.) and ImageNet classification (Krizhevsky et al.).

Information then feeds into High-Level Interpretation, where the system transitions from merely identifying objects to understanding context.

This apex tier manages complex scene understanding, spatial relationships, activity recognition, and full 3D environment reconstruction.

Advanced high-level cognitive tasks—such as visual reasoning, storytelling, and intent prediction—are linked to pioneering studies by researchers like Fei-Fei Li et al.

Ultimately, the map demonstrates how computer vision acts as an interpretive pipeline, transforming unstructured light data into structured, intelligent decisions.
